{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016BS6cwoRHCfQUf9i4xV9Xw","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_018BjzJw27KA8Cu25Lj6w3UT","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/tmp/plan.md","content":"# Elasticsearch Cluster Upgrade Migration Plan\n\n**Prepared:** 2026-06-25  \n**Cluster:** es-cluster (namespace: elasticsearch)  \n**Current Version:** 8.11.1  \n**Plan Status:** DRAFT — For review and approval. No changes applied.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Current State Snapshot\n\n### 1.1 Cluster Topology\n\n| Item | Value |\n|---|---|\n| Cluster name | es-cluster |\n| Node count | 3 (es-cluster-0, es-cluster-1, es-cluster-2) |\n| Elasticsearch version | 8.11.1 |\n| Lucene version | 9.8.0 |\n| Cluster health | Green |\n| Active primary shards | 3 |\n| Active shards (total) | 6 |\n| Unassigned shards | 0 |\n\n### 1.2 Node Configuration (all three nodes identical)\n\n- **Roles:** master, data, ingest (combined; no dedicated role separation)\n- **Node attribute:** `node.attr.tier: hot`\n- **JVM heap:** `-Xms512m -Xmx512m` (fixed 512 MiB)\n- **CPU requests/limits:** 500m / 1 CPU\n- **Memory requests/limits:** 1 Gi / 2 Gi\n- **PVC storage:** 5 Gi (ReadWriteOnce)\n- **mmap:** `node.store.allow_mmap: false`\n- **Discovery:** static seed hosts (es-cluster-0..2.es-cluster headless service)\n- **Update strategy:** `OnDelete` (pods must be deleted manually to pick up new images)\n- **Pod management policy:** `Parallel`\n- **Termination grace period:** 30 seconds\n\n### 1.3 Security Settings (non-default, explicitly disabled)\n\n```\nxpack.security.enabled: false\nxpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: false\nxpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled: false\n```\n\nSecurity is entirely disabled. All API calls are unauthenticated over plaintext HTTP.\n\n### 1.4 Index Inventory\n\n| Index | Primary Shards | Replicas | Docs | Size |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| audit-index | 3 | 1 | 0 | 1.3 KiB |\n\n### 1.5 Index-Level Non-Default Settings (audit-index)\n\n```json\n{\n  \"routing.allocation.require.tier\": \"hot\",\n  \"routing.allocation.include._tier_preference\": \"data_content\"\n}\n```\n\nShard placement is pinned to nodes with `tier=hot`. Since all current nodes carry that attribute this setting is not presently restrictive, but it will constrain placement if a warm/cold tier is added.\n\n### 1.6 Cluster-Level Settings\n\n- **Persistent:** none configured (empty)\n- **Transient:** none configured (empty)\n- All routing/allocation settings are at Elasticsearch defaults (disk watermarks: low 85%, high 90%, flood 95%).\n\n### 1.7 ILM Policies\n\nAll ILM policies present are built-in system-managed policies (prefixed with `.` or named `logs`, `metrics`, `synthetics`, `7-days-default`, `30-days-default`, `90-days-default`, `180-days-default`, `365-days-default`). None are applied to user indices.\n\n### 1.8 Snapshot Repositories\n\nNone configured. No automated backup is in place.\n\n### 1.9 Kubernetes Delivery Details\n\n- **StatefulSet update strategy:** `OnDelete` — the operator must manually delete each pod to trigger an upgrade rolling restart.\n- **PVC retention policy:** Retain on delete and on scale-down.\n- **Config source:** ConfigMap `es-config` (elasticsearch.yml mounted at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/elasticsearch.yml`).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Identified Risks and Gaps (Pre-Upgrade)\n\n### RISK-1: Security Is Completely Disabled (Critical)\n- `xpack.security.enabled: false` means no authentication, no authorization, and no TLS on HTTP or transport layers.\n- Any workload in the cluster can read or overwrite data without credentials.\n- **Action required before upgrade:** Design and apply a security configuration (TLS on transport at minimum, HTTP TLS or a reverse proxy with auth). Enabling security after data exists requires a cluster restart and credential bootstrap.\n\n### RISK-2: No Snapshot Repository / No Backup (Critical)\n- There is no snapshot repository configured. If an upgrade fails or data is corrupted, there is no restore path.\n- **Action required before upgrade:** Register at least one snapshot repository (S3, GCS, Azure Blob, or a shared filesystem PV) and take a full snapshot of all indices.\n\n### RISK-3: All Nodes Are Master-Eligible (High)\n- With 3 nodes all carrying the `master` role, losing a majority (2) during rolling restart leaves no elected master and the cluster goes read-only.\n- For an `OnDelete` upgrade where pods are restarted one at a time, losing one pod at a time is safe, but there is no dedicated master node buffer.\n- **Recommendation:** For a 3-node cluster this is acceptable if rolling restarts are strictly sequential (one pod at a time). Evaluate dedicated master nodes if the cluster grows beyond 5 nodes.\n\n### RISK-4: Heap Size Is Undersized (Medium)\n- 512 MiB heap is at the low end for a production cluster. Nodes are currently using 40–62% heap under minimal load.\n- The JVM heap should be set to no more than 50% of container memory and no more than 30 GiB.\n- **Recommendation:** Increase to `-Xms1g -Xmx1g` (matching the 2 Gi memory limit at 50%) and increase the memory limit to at least 4 Gi if the workload grows.\n\n### RISK-5: OnDelete Update Strategy Requires Manual Coordination (Medium)\n- `updateStrategy: OnDelete` does not automatically restart pods when the StatefulSet image is updated. Each pod must be manually deleted in order.\n- There is no built-in safeguard against deleting two pods simultaneously.\n- **Recommendation:** Optionally switch to `RollingUpdate` with `maxUnavailable: 1` for automated sequential restarts; or keep `OnDelete` and enforce a strict deletion procedure.\n\n### RISK-6: Disk Watermarks vs. PVC Size (Medium)\n- Each node has 5 Gi PVCs. At default high watermark (90%), allocation stops at ~4.5 Gi used per node.\n- With 3 primary shards and 1 replica on 3 nodes, data is distributed but headroom is tight.\n- **Recommendation:** Before upgrade, verify actual disk usage (`_cat/allocation`) and expand PVCs or add nodes if usage exceeds 70%.\n\n### RISK-7: Termination Grace Period Too Short (Low)\n- 30 seconds may not be enough for an Elasticsearch node to gracefully flush and leave the cluster (sync_flushed). This can lead to shard recovery overhead after restart.\n- **Recommendation:** Increase `terminationGracePeriodSeconds` to 120 seconds.\n\n### RISK-8: mmap Disabled (Performance, Low)\n- `node.store.allow_mmap: false` avoids the need to set `vm.max_map_count` on the host but degrades I/O performance for Lucene.\n- **Recommendation:** If the host kernel can be configured (`vm.max_map_count=262144` via a DaemonSet init container or node tuning), enable mmap for production workloads.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Target State for Next Upgrade Cycle\n\n### 3.1 Version Target\n\nThe recommended upgrade target is **8.17.x** (the current 8.x maintenance stream as of mid-2026), which provides:\n- Lucene 9.11+ (improved performance)\n- Full compatibility with all 8.x index formats\n- `minimum_wire_compatibility_version: 7.17.0` preserved (no 7.x nodes required)\n\nAlternatively, if the team intends to move to **9.0.x**, a full major-version plan is required (one-way migration, all indices must be created on 8.x+; no 7.x-era indices supported).\n\n### 3.2 Configuration Changes Planned\n\n| Setting | Current | Target |\n|---|---|---|\n| Image tag | 8.11.1 | 8.17.x (exact patch TBD after release review) |\n| xpack.security.enabled | false | true |\n| xpack.security.http.ssl | disabled | enabled (cert from a Kubernetes Secret) |\n| xpack.security.transport.ssl | disabled | enabled |\n| JVM heap | -Xms512m -Xmx512m | -Xms1g -Xmx1g |\n| Memory limit | 2 Gi | 4 Gi |\n| terminationGracePeriodSeconds | 30 | 120 |\n| node.store.allow_mmap | false | true (if host tuning is applied) |\n| cluster.initial_master_nodes | present | remove after first upgrade (bootstrap-only) |\n| Snapshot repository | none | register before upgrade |\n\n---\n\n## 4. Pre-Upgrade Checklist (All Must Pass Before Any Change)\n\n1. [ ] Full snapshot taken and verified (restore test in a separate namespace).\n2. [ ] Cluster health is Green (`_cluster/health`).\n3. [ ] Zero unassigned shards.\n4. [ ] Disk usage below 70% on all nodes (`_cat/allocation?v`).\n5. [ ] TLS certificates generated and stored in Kubernetes Secrets (for transport and HTTP).\n6. [ ] Security bootstrap plan reviewed (initial elastic user password, built-in users).\n7. [ ] Upgrade compatibility matrix confirmed: 8.11.1 → 8.17.x is a supported one-step upgrade.\n8. [ ] Change window scheduled and stakeholders notified.\n9. [ ] Rollback procedure documented (snapshot restore path confirmed).\n\n---\n\n## 5. Rolling Upgrade Procedure (OnDelete Strategy)\n\nThe StatefulSet uses `OnDelete`, so the upgrade is performed by updating the image tag and then manually deleting pods one at a time, waiting for each to rejoin the cluster before proceeding.\n\n### Step 1 — Disable Shard Rebalancing\n\n```bash\ncurl -X PUT \"http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_cluster/settings\" \\\n  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d '{\n    \"persistent\": {\n      \"cluster.routing.allocation.enable\": \"primaries\"\n    }\n  }'\n```\n\nThis prevents shard rebalancing while a node is down, reducing I/O and risk.\n\n### Step 2 — Update the ConfigMap\n\nApply the updated `es-config` ConfigMap with the new `elasticsearch.yml` (security settings, new heap via `ES_JAVA_OPTS` env var in the StatefulSet, etc.).\n\n### Step 3 — Update the StatefulSet Image\n\n```bash\nkubectl -n elasticsearch set image statefulset/es-cluster \\\n  elasticsearch=docker.elastic.co/elasticsearch/elasticsearch:8.17.x\n```\n\nPods do NOT restart automatically (OnDelete strategy).\n\n### Step 4 — Rolling Pod Replacement (One at a Time)\n\nRepeat for each pod (es-cluster-2, es-cluster-1, es-cluster-0 — data nodes before masters if roles were separated; in this all-roles topology, reverse ordinal order is conventional):\n\n```bash\n# Delete pod (triggers replacement with new image)\nkubectl -n elasticsearch delete pod es-cluster-2\n\n# Wait until pod is Running and Ready\nkubectl -n elasticsearch wait pod/es-cluster-2 --for=condition=Ready --timeout=300s\n\n# Verify cluster health is Green and node has rejoined\nkubectl -n elasticsearch exec curl-test -- \\\n  curl -s \"http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_cluster/health?pretty\"\n\n# Confirm all shards are assigned before moving to the next pod\nkubectl -n elasticsearch exec curl-test -- \\\n  curl -s \"http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_cat/shards?v&h=index,shard,state,node\" | grep -v STARTED || true\n```\n\nOnly proceed to the next pod when the cluster is Green.\n\n### Step 5 — Re-enable Shard Rebalancing\n\n```bash\ncurl -X PUT \"http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_cluster/settings\" \\\n  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d '{\n    \"persistent\": {\n      \"cluster.routing.allocation.enable\": null\n    }\n  }'\n```\n\n### Step 6 — Post-Upgrade Verification\n\n```bash\n# All nodes on new version\ncurl \"http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_cat/nodes?v&h=name,version\"\n\n# Cluster health Green\ncurl \"http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_cluster/health?pretty\"\n\n# audit-index settings preserved\ncurl \"http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/audit-index/_settings?pretty\"\n\n# ILM policies intact\ncurl \"http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_ilm/policy?pretty\"\n```\n\n### Step 7 — Remove cluster.initial_master_nodes\n\nAfter a successful upgrade, `cluster.initial_master_nodes` must be removed from the ConfigMap — it is only valid at cluster bootstrap and causes warnings or errors if left in place on a running cluster.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Rollback Plan\n\nIf the upgrade fails at any pod:\n\n1. Update the StatefulSet image back to `8.11.1`.\n2. Delete the affected pod — it will restart with the previous image.\n3. Verify the cluster returns to Green.\n4. If data corruption is suspected, stop writes and restore from the pre-upgrade snapshot.\n\nNote: Elasticsearch index formats are forwards-compatible but NOT always backwards-compatible across minor versions. If upgraded nodes have written new-format data, rolling back may require a full snapshot restore.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Security Enablement Plan (Separate from Version Upgrade)\n\nSecurity enablement is a breaking change that should be done as a separate maintenance window, either before or after the version upgrade (not simultaneously).\n\n### 7.1 Generate TLS Certificates\n\nUse `elasticsearch-certutil` inside a pod:\n\n```bash\n# Generate CA\nkubectl -n elasticsearch exec es-cluster-0 -- \\\n  bin/elasticsearch-certutil ca --out /tmp/elastic-stack-ca.p12 --pass \"\"\n\n# Generate node certs from CA\nkubectl -n elasticsearch exec es-cluster-0 -- \\\n  bin/elasticsearch-certutil cert --ca /tmp/elastic-stack-ca.p12 \\\n  --out /tmp/elastic-certificates.p12 --pass \"\"\n```\n\nStore certificates as Kubernetes Secrets and mount them into the pods.\n\n### 7.2 Enable Security in elasticsearch.yml\n\nAdd to ConfigMap:\n```yaml\nxpack.security.enabled: true\nxpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled: true\nxpack.security.transport.ssl.keystore.path: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/elastic-certificates.p12\nxpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: true\nxpack.security.http.ssl.keystore.path: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/elastic-certificates.p12\n```\n\n### 7.3 Bootstrap Passwords\n\nAfter restarting the cluster with security enabled, run:\n```bash\nkubectl -n elasticsearch exec es-cluster-0 -- \\\n  bin/elasticsearch-setup-passwords auto\n```\n\nStore output credentials in Kubernetes Secrets.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Index Settings Impact Assessment\n\n### audit-index\n\nCurrent non-default settings:\n- `index.routing.allocation.require.tier: hot` — pinned to hot tier nodes\n- `index.routing.allocation.include._tier_preference: data_content`\n\n**Impact of upgrade:** These settings are preserved across node restarts and version upgrades. No action required.\n\n**Impact of adding warm/cold nodes:** If warm or cold tier nodes are added in a future architecture change, this index will refuse to migrate to those tiers until `require.tier` is updated or removed. Document this constraint for future capacity planning.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Open Questions for SRE Review\n\n1. **Upgrade target version:** Confirm 8.17.x or evaluate 9.0.x. If 9.x, plan for a two-step upgrade (8.11 → 8.17 → 9.x) and audit for deprecated API usage.\n2. **Security timeline:** Should TLS/auth be enabled before or after version upgrade?\n3. **Snapshot repository:** Which storage backend is available (S3, GCS, NFS)?\n4. **Node sizing:** Is 5 Gi storage per node sufficient for projected data growth over the next 6 months?\n5. **Role separation:** Should dedicated master nodes be introduced if the cluster grows?\n6. **mmap enablement:** Can the Kubernetes nodes be tuned (`vm.max_map_count`)? Is a DaemonSet-based sysctl tuner acceptable?\n7. **Change window:** Target date and duration for each maintenance window.\n\n---\n\n*This plan is read-only. No changes have been applied to the cluster. All settings observed are unchanged.*\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1877,"cache_read_input_tokens":43039,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1877},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2fd52cb2-b7ce-4b4f-b6c1-713bc6c7bc4b","uuid":"99276017-32d4-430b-86f9-34fb629e1075","request_id":"req_011CcQ2XxrJB7dbo27i4wi2D"}
