{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017YoHwwe9J9GDsfn7UwSdpi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01JzLeNeQpMsLzdZWSaynUkL","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cat > /tmp/plan.md << 'PLANEOF'\n# Elasticsearch Cluster Upgrade Migration Plan\n\n**Prepared:** 2026-06-25\n**Cluster:** es-cluster (namespace: elasticsearch)\n**Current Version:** 8.11.1\n**Plan Status:** DRAFT — For review and approval. No changes applied.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Current State Snapshot\n\n### 1.1 Cluster Topology\n\n| Item | Value |\n|---|---|\n| Cluster name | es-cluster |\n| Node count | 3 (es-cluster-0, es-cluster-1, es-cluster-2) |\n| Elasticsearch version | 8.11.1 |\n| Lucene version | 9.8.0 |\n| Cluster health | Green |\n| Active primary shards | 3 |\n| Active shards (total) | 6 |\n| Unassigned shards | 0 |\n\n### 1.2 Node Configuration (identical across all three nodes)\n\n- **Roles:** master, data, ingest (combined; no dedicated role separation)\n- **Node attribute:** node.attr.tier: hot\n- **JVM heap:** -Xms512m -Xmx512m (fixed 512 MiB)\n- **CPU requests/limits:** 500m / 1 CPU\n- **Memory requests/limits:** 1 Gi / 2 Gi\n- **PVC storage:** 5 Gi (ReadWriteOnce)\n- **mmap:** node.store.allow_mmap: false\n- **Discovery:** static seed hosts (es-cluster-0..2.es-cluster headless service)\n- **Update strategy:** OnDelete (pods must be deleted manually to pick up new images)\n- **Pod management policy:** Parallel\n- **Termination grace period:** 30 seconds\n\n### 1.3 Security Settings (explicitly disabled)\n\n  xpack.security.enabled: false\n  xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: false\n  xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled: false\n\nAll API calls are unauthenticated over plaintext HTTP. This is the most critical gap in the current configuration.\n\n### 1.4 Index Inventory\n\n| Index | Primary Shards | Replicas | Docs | Size |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| audit-index | 3 | 1 | 0 | 1.3 KiB |\n\n### 1.5 Index-Level Non-Default Settings (audit-index)\n\n  index.routing.allocation.require.tier: hot\n  index.routing.allocation.include._tier_preference: data_content\n\nShard placement is pinned to nodes with tier=hot. Since all current nodes carry that attribute, this setting is not currently restrictive, but it will block migration to warm/cold tiers if those are added.\n\n### 1.6 Cluster-Level Settings\n\n- Persistent: none configured (empty)\n- Transient: none configured (empty)\n- All routing/allocation settings are at Elasticsearch defaults (disk watermarks: low 85%, high 90%, flood_stage 95%).\n\n### 1.7 ILM Policies\n\nAll ILM policies present are built-in system-managed policies: .deprecation-indexing-ilm-policy, .fleet-*, .monitoring-8-ilm-policy, 7-days-default, 30-days-default, 90-days-default, 180-days-default, 365-days-default, logs, metrics, synthetics, slm-history-ilm-policy, ilm-history-ilm-policy, ml-size-based-ilm-policy, watch-history-ilm-policy-16, behavioral_analytics-events-default_policy. None are applied to user indices.\n\n### 1.8 Snapshot Repositories\n\nNone configured. No automated backup is in place.\n\n### 1.9 Kubernetes Delivery Details\n\n- StatefulSet update strategy: OnDelete (manual pod deletion required per upgrade)\n- PVC retention policy: Retain on both delete and scale-down\n- Config source: ConfigMap es-config (elasticsearch.yml mounted at /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/elasticsearch.yml)\n- cluster.initial_master_nodes is currently set to all three node names (es-cluster-0, es-cluster-1, es-cluster-2); this is a bootstrap-only setting and should be removed after initial cluster formation.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Identified Risks and Gaps\n\n### RISK-1: Security Completely Disabled [Critical]\n\nxpack.security.enabled: false means no authentication, no authorization, and no TLS on HTTP or transport. Any workload in the cluster namespace can read or destroy data without credentials.\n\nAction required before upgrade: Design and apply a security configuration (TLS on transport at minimum, HTTP TLS or a reverse proxy with authentication). Enabling security after data exists requires a full cluster restart and credential bootstrap.\n\n### RISK-2: No Snapshot Repository / No Backup [Critical]\n\nThere is no snapshot repository configured. If an upgrade fails or data is corrupted, there is no restore path.\n\nAction required before upgrade: Register at least one snapshot repository (S3, GCS, Azure Blob, or a shared filesystem PV) and take a verified full snapshot of all indices.\n\n### RISK-3: All Nodes Are Master-Eligible [High]\n\nWith 3 nodes all carrying the master role, losing a majority (2 nodes) during a rolling restart leaves no elected master and the cluster becomes unavailable. For a strictly sequential (one-pod-at-a-time) OnDelete upgrade this is survivable, but there is zero buffer if a node fails unexpectedly during the window.\n\nRecommendation: For a 3-node cluster, sequential restarts are safe. Evaluate dedicated master nodes if the cluster grows beyond 5 nodes.\n\n### RISK-4: Heap Size Undersized [Medium]\n\n512 MiB heap is at the low end for a production node. Under minimal current load, nodes are already consuming 40-62% of heap. JVM GC pressure will increase as data volume grows.\n\nRecommendation: Increase to -Xms1g -Xmx1g (50% of the 2 Gi memory limit) and increase memory limit to 4 Gi if workload grows.\n\n### RISK-5: OnDelete Strategy Requires Manual Coordination [Medium]\n\nOnDelete provides no automated safeguards against deleting two pods simultaneously. A misstep during the upgrade window could leave the cluster with no quorum.\n\nRecommendation: Consider switching to RollingUpdate with maxUnavailable: 1 for automated sequential restarts, or enforce a strict manual procedure with health checks between each pod deletion.\n\n### RISK-6: Disk Watermarks vs. PVC Size [Medium]\n\nEach node has 5 Gi PVCs. At the default high watermark (90%), shard allocation is suspended at ~4.5 Gi used per node. With 3 shards and 1 replica, headroom is tight if data volume grows.\n\nRecommendation: Verify actual disk usage before upgrade. Expand PVCs or add nodes if usage exceeds 70%.\n\n### RISK-7: Termination Grace Period Too Short [Low]\n\n30 seconds may not be sufficient for Elasticsearch to flush segments and leave the cluster gracefully. This can cause shard recovery overhead after each restart.\n\nRecommendation: Increase terminationGracePeriodSeconds to 120 seconds.\n\n### RISK-8: mmap Disabled [Low - Performance]\n\nnode.store.allow_mmap: false avoids the need to tune vm.max_map_count on the host but results in lower Lucene I/O performance.\n\nRecommendation: Enable mmap if the Kubernetes nodes can be tuned (vm.max_map_count=262144 via a DaemonSet init container or node-level sysctl tuning).\n\n### RISK-9: cluster.initial_master_nodes Should Be Removed [Low]\n\ncluster.initial_master_nodes is a cluster-bootstrap-only setting. Leaving it in elasticsearch.yml after the cluster has formed is harmless in 8.x but generates deprecation warnings and may cause issues in future major versions.\n\nAction: Remove cluster.initial_master_nodes from the ConfigMap in the next maintenance window.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Target State for Next Upgrade Cycle\n\n### 3.1 Version Target\n\nRecommended upgrade target: 8.17.x (the current 8.x maintenance stream), which provides improved Lucene performance and full compatibility with all 8.x index formats. The minimum wire compatibility of 7.17.0 is preserved, requiring no 7.x node cleanup.\n\nIf the team intends to move to 9.0.x: a two-step upgrade is required (8.11.1 to 8.17.x first, then 9.0.x). All deprecated APIs used in index mappings or templates must be resolved before the 9.x jump.\n\n### 3.2 Configuration Changes Planned\n\n| Setting | Current | Target |\n|---|---|---|\n| Image tag | 8.11.1 | 8.17.x (exact patch TBD) |\n| xpack.security.enabled | false | true |\n| HTTP TLS | disabled | enabled (cert from Kubernetes Secret) |\n| Transport TLS | disabled | enabled |\n| JVM heap | 512m/512m | 1g/1g |\n| Memory limit | 2 Gi | 4 Gi |\n| terminationGracePeriodSeconds | 30 | 120 |\n| node.store.allow_mmap | false | true (conditional on host tuning) |\n| cluster.initial_master_nodes | present | remove (post-bootstrap cleanup) |\n| Snapshot repository | none | register before upgrade |\n\n---\n\n## 4. Pre-Upgrade Checklist\n\nAll items must pass before any change is applied:\n\n1. [ ] Full snapshot taken and verified (restore test in a separate namespace confirms recoverability).\n2. [ ] Cluster health is Green (_cluster/health).\n3. [ ] Zero unassigned shards.\n4. [ ] Disk usage below 70% on all nodes (_cat/allocation?v).\n5. [ ] TLS certificates generated and stored in Kubernetes Secrets.\n6. [ ] Security bootstrap plan reviewed (elastic superuser password, built-in user credentials).\n7. [ ] Upgrade compatibility matrix confirmed: 8.11.1 to 8.17.x is a supported direct upgrade path.\n8. [ ] Deprecation API reviewed for any warnings: GET /_migration/deprecations.\n9. [ ] Change window scheduled and stakeholders notified.\n10. [ ] Rollback procedure documented and snapshot restore tested.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Rolling Upgrade Procedure (OnDelete Strategy)\n\nThe StatefulSet uses OnDelete, so the operator updates the image tag and then manually deletes pods one at a time, waiting for each to rejoin before proceeding.\n\n### Step 1 — Disable Shard Rebalancing\n\n  curl -X PUT \"http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_cluster/settings\" \\\n    -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d '{\n      \"persistent\": {\"cluster.routing.allocation.enable\": \"primaries\"}\n    }'\n\n### Step 2 — Update ConfigMap\n\nApply the updated es-config ConfigMap with the new elasticsearch.yml reflecting security settings and any other configuration changes.\n\n### Step 3 — Update StatefulSet Image\n\n  kubectl -n elasticsearch set image statefulset/es-cluster \\\n    elasticsearch=docker.elastic.co/elasticsearch/elasticsearch:8.17.x\n\nPods do NOT restart automatically due to the OnDelete strategy.\n\n### Step 4 — Rolling Pod Replacement (Strictly Sequential)\n\nRepeat for each pod in reverse ordinal order (es-cluster-2, then es-cluster-1, then es-cluster-0):\n\n  # Delete pod to trigger replacement\n  kubectl -n elasticsearch delete pod es-cluster-2\n\n  # Wait for pod to be Ready\n  kubectl -n elasticsearch wait pod/es-cluster-2 --for=condition=Ready --timeout=300s\n\n  # Verify cluster is Green and all shards assigned before proceeding\n  kubectl -n elasticsearch exec curl-test -- \\\n    curl -s \"http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_cluster/health?pretty\"\n\nOnly proceed to the next pod when the cluster reports status: green.\n\n### Step 5 — Re-enable Shard Rebalancing\n\n  curl -X PUT \"http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_cluster/settings\" \\\n    -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d '{\n      \"persistent\": {\"cluster.routing.allocation.enable\": null}\n    }'\n\n### Step 6 — Post-Upgrade Verification\n\n  # All nodes on new version\n  curl \"http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_cat/nodes?v&h=name,version\"\n\n  # Cluster health Green\n  curl \"http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_cluster/health?pretty\"\n\n  # audit-index settings preserved\n  curl \"http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/audit-index/_settings?pretty\"\n\n  # ILM policies intact\n  curl \"http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_ilm/policy?pretty\"\n\n  # Deprecation warnings addressed\n  curl \"http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_migration/deprecations\"\n\n### Step 7 — Remove cluster.initial_master_nodes from ConfigMap\n\nAfter a successful upgrade, remove cluster.initial_master_nodes from the ConfigMap and perform a rolling restart to apply the clean configuration.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Rollback Plan\n\nIf the upgrade fails on any pod:\n\n1. Update the StatefulSet image back to 8.11.1.\n2. Delete the affected pod — it restarts with the original image.\n3. Verify cluster returns to Green.\n4. If data corruption is suspected, stop all writes and restore from the pre-upgrade snapshot.\n\nNote: Elasticsearch index formats are forward-compatible but NOT always backward-compatible across minor versions. If upgraded nodes have already written new-format segments, rolling back may require a full snapshot restore rather than a simple image revert.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Security Enablement Plan (Separate Maintenance Window)\n\nSecurity enablement is a breaking change and should be treated as a separate maintenance window, either before or after the version upgrade — not simultaneously, to limit blast radius.\n\n### 7.1 Generate TLS Certificates\n\n  # Generate CA\n  kubectl -n elasticsearch exec es-cluster-0 -- \\\n    bin/elasticsearch-certutil ca --out /tmp/elastic-stack-ca.p12 --pass \"\"\n\n  # Generate node certs from CA\n  kubectl -n elasticsearch exec es-cluster-0 -- \\\n    bin/elasticsearch-certutil cert --ca /tmp/elastic-stack-ca.p12 \\\n    --out /tmp/elastic-certificates.p12 --pass \"\"\n\nStore certificates as Kubernetes Secrets. Mount them into pods via volumeMounts in the StatefulSet spec.\n\n### 7.2 Updated elasticsearch.yml (security-enabled)\n\n  xpack.security.enabled: true\n  xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled: true\n  xpack.security.transport.ssl.keystore.path: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/elastic-certificates.p12\n  xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: true\n  xpack.security.http.ssl.keystore.path: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/elastic-certificates.p12\n\n### 7.3 Bootstrap Passwords\n\nAfter restarting the cluster with security enabled:\n\n  kubectl -n elasticsearch exec es-cluster-0 -- \\\n    bin/elasticsearch-setup-passwords auto\n\nStore all output credentials in Kubernetes Secrets immediately. Update any application connection strings before the maintenance window ends.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Index Settings Impact Assessment\n\n### audit-index\n\nCurrent non-default settings:\n- index.routing.allocation.require.tier: hot (pinned to hot-tier nodes)\n- index.routing.allocation.include._tier_preference: data_content\n\nImpact of upgrade: These settings survive node restarts and version upgrades unchanged. No action required during the version upgrade.\n\nImpact of adding warm/cold nodes in a future expansion: If warm or cold tier nodes are added, the audit-index will refuse to migrate off hot-tier nodes until require.tier is updated or removed. Document this constraint for future capacity planning. If tiered storage is desired, replace require.tier with _tier_preference routing.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Open Questions for SRE Review\n\n1. Upgrade target: Confirm 8.17.x or evaluate 9.0.x. If 9.x, plan for 8.11 to 8.17 to 9.x two-step path and audit deprecated API usage first.\n2. Security timeline: Should TLS/auth be enabled before or after the version upgrade?\n3. Snapshot repository: Which storage backend is available (S3, GCS, NFS PV)?\n4. Storage sizing: Is 5 Gi per node sufficient for projected data growth over the next 6 months?\n5. Node role separation: Should dedicated master nodes be introduced for additional HA guarantees?\n6. mmap enablement: Can the Kubernetes nodes be tuned (vm.max_map_count)? Is a DaemonSet-based sysctl tuner acceptable?\n7. Change window: Target date and duration for each maintenance window.\n8. Application impact: Are there client applications connecting to es-http that must be updated for TLS and credentials after security is enabled?\n\n---\n\n*This plan is read-only. No changes have been applied to the live cluster. All observed settings remain unchanged.*\nPLANEOF\necho \"Exit code: $?\"\nwc -l /tmp/plan.md","description":"Write the migration plan to a temp file"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4522,"cache_read_input_tokens":44916,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4522},"output_tokens":42,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"dia